# Mojo: canonical `text` + typed `Variant` payload

## When this helps

Use this when callers **often need both**:

1. **The original / canonical string form** ‚Äî what was written, what you round-trip, print, log, or serialize; and  
2. **Type-safe semantic access** ‚Äî a **`std.utils.Variant[T1, T2, ‚Ä¶]`** (or similar) holding the **parsed, typed** interpretation of that string.

The wrapper is **not** ‚Äúcache display text copied out of the variant.‚Äù It **pairs** a **stable textual representation** with a **typed parse result** whose meaning is: *this payload is what you get when you parse/validate that text.*

## Model

- **`text`** ‚Äî **Canonical / source representation.** This is what you treat as authoritative for the literal form.
- **`payload`** ‚Äî **The parsed, typed interpretation of `text`.** It is **derived from** `text`, not the other way around.

**Invariant:** **`payload` must be a valid interpretation of `text`.**

- If **`text` changes**, **`payload` must be reparsed** (or the whole value replaced) so the invariant holds.
- If **`payload` is mutated independently**, either **do not allow that**, or **regenerate / recanonicalize `text`** so it again matches the payload. Otherwise the pair is inconsistent.

## Construction

**Prefer** construction that **starts from `text`**, **parses and validates**, then **stores both** together ‚Äî for example a parser or factory:

```mojo
def parse_value(text: String) raises -> Value:
    ...
```

Inside, you typically: read **`text`**, run your grammar or validators, build the appropriate **`Variant`** member, then assign **`self.text`** and **`self.payload`** in one coherent path.

**Consistency:** **`text` and `payload` stay aligned because `payload` is produced by parsing/validating `text`** ‚Äî not because a string was copied from a struct before moving it into the variant.

### Constructors from member structs

A generic **`__init__[T: ‚Ä¶](out self, var item: T)`** that sets **`text`** from **`item`** and moves **`item`** into **`payload`** can still be valid **only** as an **optional convenience**: it must **produce canonical `text`** and go through the **same validation rules** as parsing (or call the same internal logic) so the invariant holds. If it is just ‚Äúserialize the struct‚Äù without matching your canonical form, prefer **`parse_value(canonical_string(...))`** instead.

Delegate **`isa[T]()`** / **`get[T]()`** to **`payload`** if you want a single access surface.

## Host object

The object that **owns** the slot (AST node, config row, command, etc.) typically:

- Stores **`var field: Value`** (or your wrapper name).
- Exposes setters that either **replace `text` and reparse**, or **replace the whole `Value`** after **`parse_value`**.

Consumers that need the literal use **`field.text`**; consumers that need semantics use **`field.isa[Foo]()`** / **`field.get[Foo]()`** ‚Äî remembering that **payload** is only trustworthy relative to **text**.

Use a **sentinel** alternative in the **`Variant`** (e.g. **`Empty`**) for ‚Äúnothing stored‚Äù if that fits your API.

## Mutable payload access

**Warning:** Exposing **mutable** access to **`payload`** (e.g. **`get` returning a mutable `ref`** that callers can alter) can **break the invariant** unless the wrapper **also** updates or **recanonicalizes `text`** on every such mutation. Safer patterns: **immutable** semantic access, **replace** the whole **`Value`** via **`parse_value`**, or **explicit** mutators that re-sync **`text`**.

## Adding an alternative

1. Extend the parser / **`parse_value`** (and validation) so a new **`text` shape** maps to a new **`Variant`** member.
2. Append the new struct to **`Variant[T1, T2, ‚Ä¶]`**.
3. Update dispatch (validators, printers) that match on **`isa`**.

## When **not** to use this

- **Uniform representation**: if every case is the same shape (e.g. a tag + one integer), prefer a **comptime tag + `value` field** (`mojo-enum-pattern.mdc`) instead of a **`Variant`** of many structs.
- **Very large or rare** alternatives: weigh **`Variant`** size and codegen cost; sometimes indirection (`Arc`, pointer to base) fits better.

## Rules (summary)

1. Treat **`text`** as the **canonical** form; **`payload`** is the **parse** of **`text`**.
2. **Primary** construction path: **`parse_value(text)`** (or equivalent) ‚Äî parse/validate, then store **both**.
3. **All** **`Variant`** members should be **`Movable`**; the variant owns the active member.
4. **Do not** let **`text` and `payload` drift**; changing one requires **reparse**, **recanonicalize**, or **replace** the whole value.
5. Prefer **`get[T]()`** only after **`isa[T]()`** is known true, or follow your codebase‚Äôs conventions for partial access.

